        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-12 14:11:17.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\ne.g. \"diff -u\"\n\nIs this shell script referenced somewhere or it's just meant to be run manually? Can't it leverage version control or at least patching instead of such extensive and unpredictable (from resulting output perspective) use of stream editor? Also looking at line 26 where it bounds the flow to a specific commit it seems hard to maintain in future releases.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "3e0439271c55d1e708b486c4a823588a6abc6ae9",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5302,
          "name": "Enbo Wang",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "wangenbo@huawei.com",
          "username": "wangeb"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-03-13 13:31:27.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 6:\n\n> Patch Set 6:\n> \n> e.g. \"diff -u\"\n> \n> Is this shell script referenced somewhere or it's just meant to be run manually? Can't it leverage version control or at least patching instead of such extensive and unpredictable (from resulting output perspective) use of stream editor? Also looking at line 26 where it bounds the flow to a specific commit it seems hard to maintain in future releases.\n\nHi,\n\nThis shell script is just to be run manually.\n\nIt bounds to a specific commit is to keep the patch files are always available.\n\nIf doesn't bound to a specific commit, the patch files may be invalid when the source CBA files in CDS code are updated in the future.\n\nI will use patching instead of sed command in the next patch set.",
        "patchset_number": 6
      },
